Whether the others are _bugs_ is up to interpretation. One might say perhaps:

* Well, pkcs11-provider checked the key type, and every providers of that type is expected to always implement those param types. (Even custom providers? Is this documented?)
* ngtcp2 knows what cipher it's working with and those ciphers are known to implement `OSSL_CIPHER_PARAM_AEAD_TAG`
* Maybe the `EVP_CIPHER_CTX` getters are OK because maybe it's an (undocumented?) requirement that _every_ `EVP_CIPHER` provider _must_ implement those properties?

At the least, I hope it's clear that this convention is fragile and prone to precarious assumptions on a very dynamic system. By replacing type-checking with an ad-hoc and less safe version of Python keyword arguments (Python rejects unknown args), OpenSSL 3.x has significantly regressed the API's robustness.

In OpenSSL 1.x, `EVP_PKEY_CTX` worked by configuring algorithm-specific parameters one by one. If you configured a parameter that wasn't relevant to the algorithm (e.g. trying to generate a P-256 RSA key), the `EVP_PKEY_CTX_ctrl` wrapper would return an error.

In OpenSSL 3.x, everything has been recast as `OSSL_PARAM`s. Unfortunately, OpenSSL decided that unrecognized `OSSL_PARAM`s are not an error. This regresses this error-checking behavior. https://github.com/openssl/openssl/issues/16912 discusses how this is bad for key import. https://github.com/openssl/openssl/issues/30640 discusses how this is bad for examining a key. It turns out to also be bad for using the key.

