When running this program I observe setup completes for all 4 examples, but *use_cert_and_key only succeeds for the first 3 examples. SSL_use_cert_and_key dereferences NULL in ssl_cert.c line 1361 under the comment `check provider-loaded pk types` when the certificate is ML-DSA.

[RFC 8446 §4.6.1](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8446#section-4.6.1) (NewSessionTicket Message) states:

> Servers MUST NOT use any value greater than 604800 seconds (7 days).

While the OpenSSL **server** correctly caps `ticket_lifetime` at 604800 in `create_ticket_prequel()`, the **client** stores whatever value the server sends without validation.

### Location

`ssl/statem/statem_clnt.c`, in `tls_process_new_session_ticket()` (~line 3170):

```c
if (!PACKET_get_net_4(pkt, &ticket_lifetime_hint)
        ...
s->session->ext.tick_lifetime_hint = ticket_lifetime_hint;
// No check that ticket_lifetime_hint <= 604800 for TLS 1.3
```

The stored value is later used in `ssl/statem/extensions_clnt.c:1389` to decide whether a ticket is still fresh:

```c
if (s->session->ext.tick_lifetime_hint < agesec) {
    /* Ticket is too old. Ignore it. */
    goto dopsksess;
}
```

With `tick_lifetime_hint = 0xFFFFFFFF` (~136 years), this check never triggers.

### Suggested Fix

Add a validation check for TLS 1.3 connections:

```c
if (SSL_CONNECTION_IS_TLS13(s) && ticket_lifetime_hint > 604800) {
    SSLfatal(s, SSL_AD_ILLEGAL_PARAMETER,
             SSL_R_INVALID_TICKET_LIFETIME);
    goto err;
}
```

Or

```c
if (SSL_CONNECTION_IS_TLS13(s) && ticket_lifetime_hint > 604800)
    ticket_lifetime_hint = 604800;
```

### Notes

- The server side already enforces this correctly (`ssl/statem/statem_srvr.c:create_ticket_prequel()`) this is only a client-side validation gap
- TLS 1.2 has no such cap, so the check should be TLS 1.3-specific
- BoringSSL enforces this client-side check

With all the BIT STRING work, we ended up with a fallible, two-out-param `ASN1_BIT_STRING_get_length` function. At the time https://github.com/openssl/openssl/issues/29184 was filed, this design made sense because `ASN1_BIT_STRING` had this implicit truncation business. That meant that the byte count of the BIT STRING was not the same as `ASN1_STRING_length`.

However, since then, https://github.com/openssl/openssl/pull/29711 removed the implicit truncation behavior (yay!). Given that, I think we can do a much simpler design. Perhaps something like:

```
// ASN1_BIT_STRING_unused_bits returns the number of unused bits in the last
// byte of |str|. If |str| is empty (i.e. |ASN1_STRING_length| is zero), this
// always returns zero. Otherwise it returns a number between 0 and 7.
uint8_t ASN1_BIT_STRING_unused_bits(const ASN1_BIT_STRING *str);
```

The byte count can then just use the existing `ASN1_STRING_length` function. I think this will be a lot easier for folks to use.

