Twelve TLS 1.3 key schedule secrets stored as fixed-size arrays in the `SSL_CONNECTION` struct (ssl/ssl_local.h:1535-1546) are never zeroed via `OPENSSL_cleanse()`. This doesn’t happen after the handshake, on  `SSL_clear()`, or on `SSL_free()`. They persist as cleartext in heap memory until the allocator reuses the pages.

This is inconsistent with how OpenSSL handles similar secrets elsewhere:
  - `SSL_SESSION_free()` cleanses master_key (ssl/ssl_sess.c:856)
  - `tls13_update_key()` cleanses local key/secret (ssl/tls13_enc.c:849)
  - `ext.secure` uses `OPENSSL_secure_clear_free` (ssl/ssl_lib.c:4628)

RFC 8446 §7.1 recommends (SHOULD) erasing intermediate secrets once all derived values are computed.

## Affected Fields

All fields in ssl/ssl_local.h lines 1535-1546, within struct ssl_connection_st:
```
  unsigned char early_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char handshake_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char resumption_master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char client_finished_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char server_finished_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char server_finished_hash[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char handshake_traffic_hash[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char client_app_traffic_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char server_app_traffic_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char exporter_master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char early_exporter_master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
```
## Affected Code Paths
1. ossl_ssl_connection_free() at ssl/ssl_lib.c:1493
> Frees all sub-objects but does not call OPENSSL_cleanse() on the secret arrays. The struct is then freed via OPENSSL_free() (= plain free(), no zeroing) at ssl/ssl_lib.c:1490.

2. ossl_ssl_connection_reset() at ssl/ssl_lib.c:572
> Called by SSL_clear() to reuse a connection object. Resets state machine, session, and extensions, but does not zero the secret arrays. In connection-pooling scenarios, secrets from previous TLS 1.3 sessions persist in the reused object.

We have a regression in our application with OpenSSL 4.0.0 where EVP_PKEY_generate fails to generate a key for an Elliptic Curve when explicit parameters are provided via OSSL_PARAM if the generator has been modified from the curve's standard default.

This specific use case is a requirement for PACE (Password Authenticated Connection Establishment) as defined in BSI TR-03110, where a mapping process results in a new ephemeral generator (G~) while maintaining the standard curve's prime field and coefficients (p,a,b).

The code succeeds in all OpenSSL 3.x versions tested (up to 3.x.x/3.5.6) but fails in 4.0.0 with:
error:08000081:elliptic curve routines::unknown group

Original code: https://github.com/Governikus/AusweisApp/blob/2.5/src/card/base/pace/ec/EcUtil.cpp#L173

